The Exact Vacuum Amplitude 

 From the commutative partition function () we may now
extract the exact expression for the noncommutative field theory defined for
any   in the following manner. We use the fact, reviewed
in section 5 of , that gauge Morita equivalence provides
a one-to-one correspondence between projective modules over different
noncommutative tori (i.e. for different 's) associated with
different topological numbers, augmented with transformations of
connections between the modules. It is an exact symmetry of the
noncommutative Yang-Mills action () which is firmly
believed to extend to the full quantum level. There are many good
pieces of evidence in support of this assumption .

In the present case, we will use the fact that Morita duality can be used
to map the quantum partition function of ordinary  
Yang-Mills theory on  onto noncommutative gauge theory with
deformation parameter . The dimensionless coupling
constant and module dimensions in () transform in this case as
 and . The
equivalence provides a one-to-one correspondence between classical
solutions in the two field theories, i.e. their partitions. The
symmetry factors  in () corresponding to
permutation of partition components of identical dimension are
preserved, as is the total number  of submodules in any given
partition . From these facts it follows that the
fluctuation factors in () are invariant under this Morita
duality only  if the indices  transform as
a=a'/s  ,
which is equivalent to the expected requirement that the cycle lengths
 be interpreted as the dimensions of submodules in the commutative
gauge theory.

With these identifications we can now straightforwardly map
() onto the exact partition function of the 
Morita equivalent noncommutative gauge theory. The key point is that
the localization arguments which led to () do not
distinguish between the commutative, rational or irrational cases
there. All of the analysis and formulas of the previous section hold
universally for any value of , and hence so should the exact
expression for the vacuum amplitude. Thus, given the generic
structure of partitions as outlined in section ,
including the general definition of , the final analytic
expression for the partition function of gauge theory on a fixed
projective module over the noncommutative torus, for any value of the
noncommutativity parameter , is given by
